{"title_page": "Costa Concordia", "text_new": "{{for|details of the 2012 grounding of the ship|Costa Concordia disaster}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin\n| infobox caption = ''Costa Concordia''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = Costa Concordia in Palma, Majorca, Spain (cropped).JPG\n| Ship caption = ''Costa Concordia'' in [[Mallorca]] (28 September 2011)\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship country = Italy\n| Ship name = ''Costa Concordia''\n| Ship owner = [[Carnival Corporation & plc]]\n| Ship flag = {{shipboxflag|Italy|civil}}\n| Ship operator = [[Costa Crociere]]\n| Ship registry = [[Genoa, Italy|Genova]], {{flag|Italy|civil}}\n| Ship route = Western Mediterranean\n| Ship ordered = 19 January 2004\n| Ship builder = [[Fincantieri|Fincantieri Sestri Ponente]], Italy\n| Ship original cost = [[Euro|\u20ac]]450 million (<small>\u00a3372 million, {{US$|570 million}}</small>)\n| Ship yard number = 6122\n| Ship way number = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = {{Start date|2005|09|02|df=y}}\n| Ship completed = \n| Ship christened = 7 July 2006<ref>{{cite web| title   =Eva Herzigova to be the Godmother of ''Costa Concordia''| url   =http://www.freesun.be/freesun_news/23_june_2006/costagodmother.html| publisher   =freesun.be| date   =21 June 2006| accessdate   =20 January 2012| url-status   =dead| archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20120117003746/http://www.freesun.be/freesun_news/23_june_2006/costagodmother.html| archivedate   =17 January 2012| df   =dmy-all}}</ref>\n| Ship acquired = 29 June 2006\n| Ship maiden voyage = 14 July 2006\n| Ship in service = July 2006\n| Ship out of service = 13 January 2012\n| Ship identification = *[[Call sign]]: IBHD\n*{{IMO Number|9320544}}\n*{{MMSI Number|247158500}}\n| Ship fate = [[Costa Concordia disaster|Capsized and sank]] in 2012 off [[Isola del Giglio]], [[Tuscany]]. Salvaged in 2015 and subsequently scrapped.\n| Ship status = Scrapped in Genoa, Italy\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"rina\">{{csr|register=RINA|id=9320544|shipname=Costa Concordia |accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n| Ship class = {{sclass-|Concordia|cruise ship}}\n| Ship tonnage = {{GT|114,147}}\n| Ship length = *{{convert|290.20|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} ([[length overall|overall]])\n*{{convert|247.4|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} ([[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]])\n| Ship beam = {{convert|35.50|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = {{convert|8.20|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|14.18|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 13\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship flag = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship power = *6&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V46C\n*{{convert|102780|hp|kW|order=flip|abbr=on}} (combined)\n| Ship propulsion = *[[Diesel-electric#Ships|Diesel-electric]]; two shafts\n*[[Alstom]] propulsion motors (2&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;21&nbsp;MW)\n*Two fixed pitch propellers\n| Ship speed = *{{convert|19.6|kn|0}} (service)\n*{{convert|23|kn|0}} (maximum)\n| Ship capacity = 3780 passengers\n| Ship crew = 1100\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Costa Concordia''''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8k\u0254sta kon\u02c8k\u0254rdja}}) was a [[cruise ship]] operated by [[Costa Cruises|Costa Crociere]]. She was the first of the [[Concordia-class cruise ship|''Concordia''-class cruise ships]], followed by similar ships ''[[Costa Serena]]'', ''[[Costa Pacifica]]'', ''[[Costa Favolosa]]'' and ''[[Costa Fascinosa]]'', and ''[[Carnival Splendor]]'' built for [[Carnival Cruise Lines|Carnival Cruise Line]]. When the {{GT|114,137|disp=long|display=first}} ''Costa Concordia'' and her [[sister ship]]s entered service, they were among the largest ships built in Italy until the construction of the {{GT|130,000|link=off}} {{sclass-|Dream|cruise ship|1}}s.\n\nOn 13 January 2012 at 21:45, [[Costa Concordia disaster|''Costa Concordia'' struck a rock]] in the [[Tyrrhenian Sea]] just off the eastern shore of [[Isola del Giglio]]. This tore open a {{convert|50|m|abbr=on}} gash on the [[Port and starboard|port]] side of her hull, which soon flooded parts of the engine room, cutting power from the engines and ship services. With water flooding in and the ship [[List (watercraft)|listing]], she drifted back towards the island and grounded near shore, then rolled onto her starboard side, lying in an unsteady position on a rocky underwater ledge.\n\nThe evacuation of ''Costa Concordia'' took over six hours, and of the 3,229 passengers and 1,023 crew known to have been aboard, 32 died. [[Francesco Schettino]], the ship's captain at that time, was subsequently found guilty of manslaughter, causing a maritime accident, and [[The captain goes down with the ship|abandoning his ship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36421474|title=Concordia skipper's sentence upheld|date=2016-05-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> The wreck was salvaged three years after the incident and then towed to the port of Genoa, where scrapping operations began.<ref name=\"Arrival in Genoa\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28508387|title=Costa Concordia wreck enters Genoa port for scrapping|date=27 July 2014|work=BBC news europe|accessdate=27 July 2014|publisher=BBC|agency=BBC}}</ref>\n\n== Concept and construction ==\n[[File:Costa Concordia in Piraeus.jpg|thumb|left|''Costa Concordia'' in [[Piraeus]], [[Greece]] on 30 November 2006]]\n''Costa Concordia'' was ordered in 2004 by [[Carnival Corporation]] from [[Fincantieri]] and built in the [[Sestri Ponente]] yard in [[Genoa]],<ref name=\"Fincantieri\">{{cite press release| title= Costa Crociere Orders A New Ship From Fincantieri With An Investment Of Around 450 Million Euros| url=http://www.fincantieri.it/cms/data/browse/news/000161.aspx| publisher=Fincantieri| date=19 January 2004| accessdate = 2 September 2011}}</ref> as yard number 6122.<ref name=Fakta /> At the vessel's [[ship naming and launching|launch]] at Sestri Ponente on 2&nbsp;September 2005,<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite press release| title=''Costa Concordia'', The Largest Italian Cruise Ship, is Launched in Genoa| url=http://www.fincantieri.it/cms/data/browse/news/000193.aspx| publisher=Fincantieri| date=2 September 2005| accessdate = 2 September 2011}}</ref> the champagne bottle, released by model [[Eva Herzigov\u00e1]], failed to break when swung against the hull the first time, an inauspicious omen in [[Sailors%27_superstitions|maritime superstition]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Levy |first=Megan |title=Cursed Concordia 'born bad, ended up worse' |url=http://www.smh.com.au/travel/travel-incidents/cursed-concordia-born-bad-ended-up-worse-20120116-1q1w2.html |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref> The ship was delivered to Costa on 30&nbsp;June 2006.<ref name=\"Fincantieri3\">{{cite press release| title=Costa Crociere Takes Delivery From Fincantieri Of The New Flagship ''Costa Concordia'' |url =http://www.fincantieri.it/cms/data/browse/news/000065.aspx |publisher  = [[Fincantieri]]| date=30 June 2006 |accessdate = 2 September 2011}}</ref> It cost [[Euro|\u20ac]]450 million (\u00a3372 million, {{US$|570 million}}) to build.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|title=Italy cruise ship ''Costa Concordia'' aground near Giglio|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16558910|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=14 January 2012|accessdate=14 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64gKkECCf?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16558910 \n|archivedate=14 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy}}</ref>\nThe name ''[[wikt:concordia|Concordia]]'' was intended to express the wish for \"continuing harmony, unity, and peace between [[Europe]]an nations.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Malta on new liner's itinerary \n |url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20050919/local/malta-on-new-liners-itinerary.77802 \n |date=19 September 2005 \n |publisher=[[The Times (Malta)|The Times of Malta]] \n |accessdate=15 January 2012 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64hh6bzyK?url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20050919/local/malta-on-new-liners-itinerary.77802 \n |archivedate=15 January 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n''Costa Concordia'' was {{convert|290.20|m|ftin|0}} long, had a beam of {{convert|35.50|m|abbr=on}} and drew {{convert|8.20|m|abbr=on}} of water. She had a Diesel-electric power plant consisting of six [[V12 engine|12-cylinder]] [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V46C four-stroke medium-speed [[Diesel engine|Diesel generating sets]] with a combined output of {{convert|102780|hp|MW|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"tradewinds\">{{Citation\n | title    = Costa Concordia 3,780 Berths, Cruise Vessel, Built 2006\n | url     = http://www.tradewindsnews.com/vessel?id=82C54167A64F8DE7\n | work    = [[TradeWinds (newspaper)|TradeWinds]]<br />Ship data from: Clarkson Research Services Limited\n | access-date = 28 January 2012\n}}</ref> These main generators provided power for all shipboard consumers from propulsion motors to hotel functions like lighting and air conditioning. The ship was propelled by two 21-megawatt electric motors coupled to fixed-pitch propellers.<ref>{{cite book\n | title    = Generazione di Energia A Bordo di Navi da Crociera\n | publisher  = Cetena\n | page    = 7\n | url     = http://diem.uniud.it/Conf_energia_navi_19-05-09.pdf\n | access-date = \n}}{{dead link|date=December 2012}}</ref> Her design service speed was {{convert|19.6|kn|0}},<ref name=Fakta>{{cite web\n | title    = M/S Costa Concordia\n | url     = http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/costa_concordia_2006.htm\n | work    = Fakta om Fartyg\n | language  = Swedish\n | access-date = 14 January 2012\n}}</ref> but during sea trials, she achieved a speed of {{convert|23|kn|lk=on|0}}.\n\n== Layout ==\n''Costa Concordia'' had 13 public decks, each named after a European state. Deck 1 was the lowest:<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Costa Concordia deck plans \n |url=http://www.atc.fi/old/decks/Costa_Concordia_deck_plans.pdf \n |publisher=ATC Cruises Ltd. \n |accessdate=30 December 2012\n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030040433/http://www.atc.fi/old/decks/Costa_Concordia_deck_plans.pdf \n |archivedate=30 October 2012 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n{|\n| valign=top |\n* Deck 1 Olanda (''Holland'')\n* Deck 2 Svezia (''Sweden'')\n* Deck 3 Belgio (''Belgium'')\n* Deck 4 Grecia (''Greece'')\n* Deck 5 Italia (''Italy'')\n* Deck 6 Gran Bretagna (''Great Britain''){{nb5}} {{nb5}}\n* Deck 7 Irlanda (''Ireland'')\n| valign=top |\n* Deck 8 Portogallo (''Portugal'')\n* Deck 9 Francia (''France'')\n* Deck 10 Germania (''Germany'')\n* Deck 11 Spagna (''Spain'')\n* Deck 12 Austria (''Austria'')\n* Deck 13 Polonia (''Poland'')\n|}\n\n== Amenities ==\n''Costa Concordia'' was outfitted with approximately 1,500 cabins; 505 with private balconies, and 55 with direct access to the Samsara Spa, which were considered Spa staterooms; 58&nbsp;suites had private balconies and 12 had direct access to the spa.{{clarify|date=January 2016}} ''Costa Concordia'' had one of the world's largest exercise facility areas at sea, the Samsara Spa, a two-level, {{convert|6000|m2|-2|abbr=on}} fitness center, with gym, a [[thalassotherapy]] pool, [[sauna]], [[Turkish bath]] and a solarium. The ship had four swimming pools, two with retractable roofs, five jacuzzis, five spas, and a poolside movie theatre on the main pool deck.<ref name=\"Costa\">{{cite web| title= Company Profile| url= http://www.costacruisesasia.com/B2C/PAO/Corporate/The+company/aboutourselves/aboutourselves.htm |publisher= [[Costa Crociere|Costa Crociere dba Costa Cruises]] |year= 2011 |accessdate= 2 September 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110708194121/http://www.costacruisesasia.com/B2C/PAO/Corporate/The+company/aboutourselves/aboutourselves.htm |archivedate= 8 July 2011 |df= dmy-all}}</ref> There were also five on-board restaurants, with Club Concordia and Samsara taking reservations-only dining. There were thirteen bars, including a cigar and [[Cognac (brandy)|cognac]] bar and a coffee and chocolate bar. Entertainment options included a three-level theatre, [[casino]], a futuristic disco, a children's area equipped with [[video game]]s and a basketball court. She also had aboard a [[Grand Prix motor racing]] simulator and an [[internet caf\u00e9]].<ref name=\"nypost\">{{cite news\n |agency=The Associated Press \n |title=At least 3 dead as cruise ship runs aground; captain arrested \n |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/international/three_coast_several_missing_after_Ztwzh4pOyI28VzooFByOnM/2 \n |newspaper=The New York Post \n |date=14 January 2012 \n |accessdate=30 December 2012\n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418212843/http://www.nypost.com/p/news/international/three_coast_several_missing_after_Ztwzh4pOyI28VzooFByOnM/2 \n |archivedate=18 April 2012 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n\n=== 2008 bow damage ===\nOn 22 November 2008, ''Costa Concordia'' suffered damage to her bow when high winds over the [[Sicily|Sicilian]] city of [[Palermo]] pushed the ship against its dock. There were no injuries and repairs started soon after.<ref name=\"nypost\" /><ref name=ToM>{{cite news\n | title    = Cruise liner damaged after leaving Malta\n | url     = http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20081123/local/cruise-liner-damaged-after-leaving-malta.234247\n | publisher  = [[The Times (Malta)|The Times of Malta]]\n | date    = 23 November 2008\n | accessdate = 12 January 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | title    = Costa Concordia search operation resumes (underwater video)\n | url     = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16660403\n | work  = [[BBC News Online]]\n | date    = 12 January 2012\n | accessdate = 21 January 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Costa Concordia in 2009.jpg|thumb|''Costa Concordia'' after repairs on 31 July 2009]]\n\n===2012 grounding and partial sinking===\n{{Main|Costa Concordia disaster|l1=Costa Concordia disaster}}\n[[File:Cruise Ship Costa Concordia in Genoa Harbour - November 2010.jpg|thumb|''Costa Concordia'' in [[Genoa]], Italy on 24 November 2010]]\nOn 13 January 2012, under the command of Captain [[Francesco Schettino]], in calm seas and overcast weather, after departing [[Civitavecchia]], the port for Rome, Italy, on a 7-night cruise, at 21:45 local time (UTC+1), ''Costa Concordia'' hit a rock off [[Isola del Giglio]] ({{coord|42|21|55|N|10|55|17|E |name= Costa Concordia 2012 grounding |display=inline}}), on the western coast of Italy about {{convert|100|km|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Rome]].<ref name=\"rock1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/23/world/europe/costa-concordia-may-have-had-unregistered-passengers.html|title=Costa Concordia May Have Had Unregistered Passengers|author=Gaia Pianigiani|date=22 January 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"rock2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/24/costa-concordia-captain-blame-prosecutor|title=Costa Concordia captain not solely to blame, says prosecutor|author=John Hooper|date=24 January 2012|work=The Guardian |accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> A {{convert|53|m|ft|0|adj=on}} long gash was made in the port-side hull, along 3 compartments of the engine room (deck 0); resulting in power losses, leading to a loss of propulsion and loss of electrical systems, which crippled the ship. Taking on water, the vessel [[List (watercraft)|listed]] to the port side. Twenty-four minutes later, strong winds pushed the vessel back to Giglio Island, where she [[Ship grounding|grounded]] {{convert|500|m|yd|abbr=on}} north of the village of [[Giglio Porto]], resting on her [[Port and starboard|starboard]] side in shallow waters, with most of her starboard side underwater.<ref name=\"hole1\">{{Citation|title=Naufragio al Giglio, tre morti annegati Fermati comandante e primo ufficiale, Corriere de la Sera|date=14 January 2012|url=http://www.corriere.it/cronache/12_gennaio_14/nave-crociera-incagliata-morti_da423a42-3e72-11e1-8b52-5f77182bc574.shtml|newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]]|language=Italian |accessdate=30 December 2012}} Confirms that vessel was holed.</ref><ref name=\"hole2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/christopherbooker/9030330/The-EU-ignored-years-of-expert-warnings-on-cruise-ship-safety.html|title=The EU ignored years of expert warnings on cruise ship safety|author=Christopher Book|date=21 January 2012 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=30 December 2012}} Discusses stability issue when large modern ships are holed. Explains heeling first in direction of hole, then in opposite direction.</ref><ref name=\"BBC16561382\">{{cite news\n | first    = Alexis\n | last    = Akwagyiram\n | title    = Italy cruise ship Costa Concordia: Search for missing\n | url     = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16561382\n | work    = [[BBC News Online]]\n | date    = 14 January 2012\n | accessdate = 14 January 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Collision of Costa Concordia 24.jpg|thumb|right|''Costa Concordia'' after dawn with lifeboats at shore]]\nAlmost half of the ship remained above water, but it was in danger of sinking completely into a trough {{convert|70|m|ft|0}} deep.<ref>{{cite magazine\n |author=Marco Breath \n |title=Concordia at \u2018High Risk\u2019 of Sinking, Italian Minister Says \n |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-01-19/concordia-at-high-risk-of-sinking-italian-minister-says.html\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120722185616/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-01-19/concordia-at-high-risk-of-sinking-italian-minister-says.html\n |url-status=dead\n |archivedate=22 July 2012\n |magazine=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] \n |date=23 January 2012 \n |accessdate=31 December 2012\n}}</ref> Despite the gradual sinking of the ship, its complete loss of power, and its proximity to shore in calm seas, an order to abandon ship was not issued until over an hour after the initial impact. Although international maritime law requires all passengers to be evacuated within 30 minutes of an order to abandon ship, the evacuation of ''Costa Concordia'' took over six hours. At the time, she was carrying 3,206 passengers and 1,023 crew members.<ref name=\"CarnivalCorporation\">{{cite web\n | title    = Carnival Corporation & plc Statement Regarding Costa Concordia\n | url     = http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=200767&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1648204\n | publisher  = [[Carnival Corporation & plc]]\n | date    = 14 January 2012\n | accessdate = 24 January 2012\n}}</ref><ref name=\"AP140112\">{{cite news\n |last=Winfield \n |first=Nicole \n |author2=Frances D'Emilio \n |title=Coast guard: cruise ship runs aground off Italy, 3 bodies found; helicopters rescue others \n |url=http://www.wxyz.com/dpp/homepage_showcase/coast-guard-cruise-ship-runs-aground-off-italy-3-bodies-found-helicopters-rescue-others \n |publisher=[[WXYZ-TV]] \n |agency=The Associated Press \n |date=14 January 2012 \n |accessdate=24 January 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116220935/http://www.wxyz.com/dpp/homepage_showcase/coast-guard-cruise-ship-runs-aground-off-italy-3-bodies-found-helicopters-rescue-others \n |archivedate=16 January 2012 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> The accident resulted in 32 fatalities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/glogin?URI=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2014%2F05%2F14%2Fworld%2Feurope%2Fport-vies-to-dismantle-italian-cruise-ship.html%3F_r%3D0|title=Aging Tuscan Port Vies to Dismantle Costa Concordia|last=Pianigiani|first=Gaia|date=13 May 2014 |newspaper=NYTimes|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-17472345 |title=Costa Concordia: Five more bodies found|date=22 March 2012 |work=BBC News |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> The body of the last missing person, Indian crew member Russel Rebello, was recovered on 3 November 2014.<ref name=\"NBC3Nov\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/italy-corpse-found-costa-concordia-wreck-assumed-be-russel-rebello-n239981|title=Italy: Corpse Found in Costa Concordia Wreck 'Assumed' to Be Russel Rebello|date=3 November 2014|work=NBC News|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Salvage====\n{{Main|Costa Concordia disaster#Salvage|l1=''Costa Concordia'' salvage}}\n[[File:Costa Concordia salvage July crop.jpg|thumb|right|''Costa Concordia'' salvage operation in progress]]\n\nAn initial assessment by salvage expert company [[Smit International]] estimated that the removal of ''Costa Concordia'' and her 2,380 tonnes of fuel<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/15/us-italy-ship-idUSTRE80D08220120115|title=Two more bodies found on ship, three people rescued|date=15 January 2012|work=[[Reuters]] |last2=Denti |first2=Antonio |first1=Gavin|last1=Jones |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | title    = Two more bodies found in Costa Concordia shipwreck\n | url     = https://calgaryherald.com/news/more+bodies+found+Costa+Concordia+shipwreck/6037951/story.html\n | work    = The Calgary Herald\n | date    = 23 January 2012\n | accessdate = 23 January 2012\n | archiveurl = http://www.recentnews.ca/two-more-bodies-found-in-costa-concordia-shipwreck/ <!-- vandalism ? http://scs.mathletics.com/SignInIFrame.asp?ccode=CAN&host=www.mathletics.ca --> \n | archivedate = 31 December 2012\n}}</ref> could take up to 10 months.<ref name=BBC16782481>{{cite news\n | title    = Costa Concordia recovery 'will take up to 10 months'\n | url     = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16782481\n | work    = BBC News\n | date    = 29 January 2012\n | accessdate = 30 January 2012\n}}</ref> Smit advised that the ship had been damaged beyond the hope of economical repair and recommended it be written off as a [[constructive total loss]]. Smit was soon contracted to initially remove only Concordia's fuel.\n\nDuring the fuel removal operation, Smit reported that the ship had shifted {{convert|24|in|cm|-1|order=flip|abbr=on}} in the three weeks since her grounding, but that there was no immediate prospect of her breaking up or sinking deeper.<ref>{{cite news|title= Costa Concordia: stricken cruise ship has shifted 24 inches|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/9069093/Costa-Concordia-stricken-cruise-ship-has-shifted-24-inches.html| work= The Daily Telegraph|date = 8 February 2012| accessdate = 2 May 2012}}</ref> Removal of the fuel from the various fuel tanks distributed throughout the ship was completed in March 2012, later than Smit's initial estimates. This cleared the way to arrange for the ultimate salvaging and scrapping of the ship.\n\nOn 17 September 2013, ''Costa Concordia'' was brought to a vertical position through a [[Parbuckle_salvage|parbuckling]] procedure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2013/sep/16/concordia-salvage-operation-giglio-parbuckling-live-updates|title=Costa Concordia: salvage teams begin to right cruise ship \u2013 live updates|date=16 September 2013|author=Walker, Peter |accessdate=17 September 2013 |work=The Guardian |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fglobal%2F2013%2Fsep%2F16%2Fconcordia-salvage-operation-giglio-parbuckling-live-updates&date=2013-09-18|archivedate=18 September 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Parbuckling Project: Concordia wreck removal project informative website|url=http://www.theparbucklingproject.com/page.php?page=progetto|accessdate=13 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917133020/http://www.theparbucklingproject.com/page.php?page=progetto|archivedate=17 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The cost for salvaging the ship increased to $799 million.<ref>{{cite news |author=Gaia Pianigiani and Alan Cowell |title=Crews Right Cruise Ship in Waters Off Italy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/17/world/europe/operation-to-raise-costa-concordia-cruise-liner-in-italy.html |work=The New York Times |date=16 September 2013 |accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref> In addition, the ship had suffered severe hull deformations in two places. Titan Salvage, the company directing the salvage operations, estimated that the next phase of the salvage operation would be completed by early-to-mid-2014. After this \"floating\" operation, the ship would be towed to a salvage yard on the Italian mainland for scrapping or \"breaking\".<ref>{{cite news| author=Barbie Latza Nadeau| title=Costa Concordia salvage: Island celebrations and relief |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/17/world/europe/costa-concordia/?hpt=tr_c2 |work=CNN |date=17 September 2013 |accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 July 2014, work commenced to refloat ''Costa Concordia'' in preparation for towing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/14/costa-concordia-salvage-operation-refloat-liner|title=Costa Concordia: salvage team begins operation to refloat doomed liner |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=14 July 2014 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> At this point, the costs had risen to \u20ac1 billion. Including tow cost, \u20ac100 million for the ship to be broken up for scrap and the cost of repairing damage to Giglio island, the estimated final cost was expected to be \u20ac1.5 billion ($2 billion).<ref name=\"Reuters20140706\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/06/italy-concordia-costs-idUSL6N0PH0EO20140706 ''Costa Concordia capsizing costs over $2 billion for owners''] Maria Sheahan, Reuters.com, 6 July 2014.</ref><ref name=\"GeargeHatcher20140709\">[http://disasteratsea.com/index.php/costa-concordia-owner-faces-2-billion-in-costs/ ''Costa Concordia owner faces $2 billion in costs''] George Hatcher, ''Disaster at Sea'' blog, 9 July 2014.</ref> On 23 July, having been refloated, the ship commenced its final journey under tow at a speed of {{convert|2|kn|0}}, with a 14-ship escort, to be scrapped in Genoa.<ref name=\"FinalVoyage\">{{cite news|title=Rusting luxury liner Costa begins final voyage|url=http://www.europenews.net/index.php/sid/224057463/scat/88176adfdf246af5/ht/Rusting-luxury-liner-Costa-begins-final-voyage|accessdate=23 July 2014|publisher=Europe News.Net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729235427/http://www.europenews.net/index.php/sid/224057463/scat/88176adfdf246af5/ht/Rusting-luxury-liner-Costa-begins-final-voyage|archive-date=29 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/costa-concordia-makes-final-voyage-to-its-scrapyard-grave/story-fnizu68q-1226999771994|title=The Concordia makes its final voyage|work=NewsComAu |accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref> It arrived at port on 27 July, after a four-day journey. It was moored to a seawall at the port, awaiting dismantling processes.<ref name=\"CostaArrival\">{{cite news|title=Costa Concordia wreck completes final journey|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/10994004/Costa-Concordia-comes-home-to-die.html|accessdate=28 July 2014|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=\"CostaInterior\">{{cite news|title=Costa Concordia in pictures: Inside the cruise liner after two years underwater|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/worldnews/10985345/Costa-Concordia-in-pictures-Inside-the-cruise-liner-after-two-years-underwater.html|accessdate=5 January 2015|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Costa Concordia Abwracken.jpg|thumb|left|''Costa Concordia'' on 12 September 2015, being scrapped in the Superbacino dock in Genoa, Italy]]\n\nOn 11 May 2015, following initial dismantling, but still kept afloat by the salvage sponsons, the hull was towed {{convert|10|mi|km}} to the Superbacino dock in Genoa for removal of the upper decks.<ref>{{cite news |\nurl=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/160283/costa-concordia-to-embark-on-its-final-journey/ |date=7 May 2015 |title=Costa Concordia to embark on its final journey |publisher= World Maritime News}}</ref> The last of the sponsons were removed in August 2016 and the hull was taken in to a drydock on 1 September for final dismantling.<ref name=WMN201091>{{cite web |url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/201091/costa-concordia-sets-off-on-final-voyage-to-scrapyard/ |title=Costa Concordia Sets Off on Final Voyage to Scrapyard |publisher=World Maritime News |date=2 September 2016 |accessdate=4 September 2016}}</ref> Scrapping of the ship was completed on 7 July 2017.<ref name=WMN225190>{{cite web |url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/225190/costa-concordia-saga-comes-to-an-end/ |title=Costa Concordia Saga Comes to an End |publisher=World Maritime News |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4119840/Ghost-ship-Wreck-tragic-Costa-Concordia-torn-apart-scrap-shipyard-five-years-cruise-liner-capsized-killing-32-people.html|title=Ghost ship: Wreck of tragic Costa Concordia is torn apart for scrap|author=|date=|website=dailymail.co.uk|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn 2010, ''Costa verde'' provided the setting for [[Jean-Luc Godard]]'s film ''[[Film Socialisme|Socialisme]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n | first    = Xan\n | last    = Brooks\n | title    = Costa Concordia provides setting for a 2010 Jean-Luc Godard film\n | url     = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/15/costa-concordia-jean-luc-godard\n | work    = The Guardian\n | date    = 15 January 2012\n | accessdate = 16 January 2012\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, U.S. poet and singer [[Patti Smith]] wrote and recorded parts of her album ''[[Banga (album)|Banga]]'' aboard the ship. The CD booklet includes photos taken of Smith and her band during their cruise.\n\nOn 11 April 2012, a documentary broadcast in the United Kingdom, titled ''Terror at Sea: The Sinking of the Costa Concordia'', and another first broadcast on Channel 4, titled ''The Sinking of the Concordia: Caught on Camera'', featured footage recorded by the passengers and crew.\n\nOn 14 July 2012, a documentary titled ''Cruise Ship Disaster: Inside the Concordia'', was first broadcast on the [[Discovery Channel]], ''CNN Presents: Cruise to Disaster'', first broadcast by [[CNN]]<ref>{{Citation| title= CNN Presents: Cruise to Disaster|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1207/14/cp.01.html| work=CNN| accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> and another, titled ''Inside Costa Concordia: Voices of Disaster'', was first broadcast by the [[National Geographic Channel]].<ref>{{Citation| title=Inside Costa Concordia: Voices of Disaster| url= http://natgeotv.com/asia/inside-costa-concordia-voices-of-disaster| publisher=National Geographic Channel| accessdate = 31 December 2012}}</ref> The season 39 ''[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]'' episode \"Why Ships Sink\" discusses the sinking of ''Costa Concordia''.<ref>{{Citation| author=Challis, J.| title=Nova: Why Ships Sink| url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/tech/why-ships-sink.html| publisher=[[PBS]], [[WGBH-TV|WGBH Educational Foundation]]| work=[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]| year=2012| accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> A later ''[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]'' season 42 episode \"Sunken Ship Rescue\" featured the salvage effort and race to refloat and remove the badly damaged Costa Concordia from the accident scene before the ship could break apart, risking an environmental catastrophe.<ref>{{Citation| author=WGBH Boston| title=Nova: Sunken Ship Rescue| url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/tech/sunken-ship-rescue.html| publisher=[[PBS]], [[WGBH-TV|WGBH Educational Foundation]]| work=[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]| year=2015|accessdate =21 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February 2013, ABC's ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'' aired a special on the sinking and interviews with the survivors following the engine fire on {{ship||Carnival Triumph}}.<ref>{{cite news | author=Lateef Mungin and Steve Almasy | title=Crippled cruise ship returns; passengers happy to be back | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/02/14/travel/cruise-ship-fire/index.html | work=CNN | date=15 February 2013 | accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn Paolo Sorrentino's 2013 film ''[[The Great Beauty]]'', the wreckage of ''Costa Concordia'' is featured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/09/movies/paolo-sorrentinos-great-beauty-explores-italys-decline.html|title=Paolo Sorrentino\u2019s \u2018Great Beauty\u2019 Explores Italy\u2019s Decline|last=Donadio|first=Rachel|date=8 September 2013 |work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 January 2018 |language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn the 2016 album ''Teens of Denial'', \"The Ballad of the Costa Concordia\", written by Will Toledo from indie rock band [[Car Seat Headrest]], uses the disaster as a metaphor for a personal breakdown.<ref>{{cite magazine |\nurl=http://www.bkmag.com/2016/06/21/20-best-songs-of-2016-so-far/?singlepage=1 | date=21 June 2012 |title=A Highly Subjective List of the 20 Best Songs of 2016 (So Far) |magazine=Brooklyn Magazine}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category multi|Costa Concordia (ship, 2006)|January 2012 grounding of the Costa Concordia (ship, 2006)}}\n* [http://stefanbatoryoceanliner.weebly.com/Costa-Concordia-Disaster.html Personal account by passenger Peter Wieslaw Grajda]\n* [http://firenze.repubblica.it/cronaca/2012/01/14/foto/le_scole_ecco_gli_scogli_sulle_carte_nautiche-28110610/1/ Nautical chart and satellite photo of grounding site]\u2014''[[la Repubblica]]''\n* [http://blog.flickr.net/en/2012/01/16/costa-concordia-run-aground-off-the-italian-coast/ Flickr Blog 16 January 2012 : Costa Concordia run aground off the Italian coast]\n* ''[http://www.maritime-executive.com/article/costa-concordia-ready-for-last-journey Costa Concordia Ready for Last Journey]''\n* ''[http://www.maritime-executive.com/article/costa-concordias-million-dollar-recycling-plan Costa Concordia's Million Dollar Recycling Plan]''\n\n{{Portal bar|Italy|Transport}}\n{{List of ships built by Fincantieri}}\n{{Costa Cruises}}\n{{Concordia class}}\n{{2012 shipwrecks}}\n{{italic title|noerror}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2005 ships]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2012]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Genoa]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Fincantieri]]\n[[Category:Ships of Costa Cruises]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk in collisions]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Mediterranean]]\n[[Category:2012 in Italy]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents involving cruise ships]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|details of the 2012 grounding of the ship|Costa Concordia disaster}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin\n| infobox caption = ''Costa Concordia''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = Costa Concordia in Palma, Majorca, Spain (cropped).JPG\n| Ship caption = ''Costa Concordia'' in [[Mallorca]] (28 September 2011)\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship country = Italy\n| Ship name = ''Costa Concordia''\n| Ship owner = [[Carnival Corporation & plc]]\n| Ship flag = {{shipboxflag|Italy|civil}}\n| Ship operator = [[Costa Crociere]]\n| Ship registry = [[Genoa, Italy|Genova]], {{flag|Italy|civil}}\n| Ship route = Western Mediterranean\n| Ship ordered = 19 January 2004\n| Ship builder = [[Fincantieri|Fincantieri Sestri Ponente]], Italy\n| Ship original cost = [[Euro|\u20ac]]450 million (<small>\u00a3372 million, {{US$|570 million}}</small>)\n| Ship yard number = 6122\n| Ship way number = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = {{Start date|2005|09|02|df=y}}\n| Ship completed = \n| Ship christened = 7 July 2006<ref>{{cite web| title   =Eva Herzigova to be the Godmother of ''Costa Concordia''| url   =http://www.freesun.be/freesun_news/23_june_2006/costagodmother.html| publisher   =freesun.be| date   =21 June 2006| accessdate   =20 January 2012| url-status   =dead| archiveurl   =https://web.archive.org/web/20120117003746/http://www.freesun.be/freesun_news/23_june_2006/costagodmother.html| archivedate   =17 January 2012| df   =dmy-all}}</ref>\n| Ship acquired = 29 June 2006\n| Ship maiden voyage = 14 July 2006\n| Ship in service = July 2006\n| Ship out of service = 13 January 2012\n| Ship identification = *[[Call sign]]: IBHD\n*{{IMO Number|9320544}}\n*{{MMSI Number|247158500}}\n| Ship fate = [[Costa Concordia disaster|Capsized and sank]] in 2012 off [[Isola del Giglio]], [[Tuscany]]. Salvaged in 2015 and subsequently scrapped.\n| Ship status = Scrapped in Genoa, Italy\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"rina\">{{csr|register=RINA|id=9320544|shipname=Costa Concordia |accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n| Ship class = {{sclass-|Concordia|cruise ship}}\n| Ship tonnage = {{GT|114,147}}\n| Ship length = *{{convert|290.20|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} ([[length overall|overall]])\n*{{convert|247.4|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} ([[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]])\n| Ship beam = {{convert|35.50|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = {{convert|8.20|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|14.18|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 13\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship flag = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship power = *6&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V46C\n*{{convert|102780|hp|kW|order=flip|abbr=on}} (combined)\n| Ship propulsion = *[[Diesel-electric#Ships|Diesel-electric]]; two shafts\n*[[Alstom]] propulsion motors (2&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;21&nbsp;MW)\n*Two fixed pitch propellers\n| Ship speed = *{{convert|19.6|kn|0}} (service)\n*{{convert|23|kn|0}} (maximum)\n| Ship capacity = 3780 passengers\n| Ship crew = 1100\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Costa Concordia''''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8k\u0254sta kon\u02c8k\u0254rdja}}) was a [[cruise ship]] operated by [[Costa Cruises|Costa Crociere]]. She was the first of the [[Concordia-class cruise ship|''Concordia''-class cruise ships]], followed by similar ships ''[[Costa Serena]]'', ''[[Costa Pacifica]]'', ''[[Costa Favolosa]]'' and ''[[Costa Fascinosa]]'', and ''[[Carnival Splendor]]'' built for [[Carnival Cruise Lines|Carnival Cruise Line]]. When the {{GT|114,137|disp=long|display=first}} ''Costa Concordia'' and her [[sister ship]]s entered service, they were among the largest ships built in Italy until the construction of the {{GT|130,000|link=off}} {{sclass-|Dream|cruise ship|1}}s.\n\nOn 13 January 2012 at 21:45, [[Costa Concordia disaster|''Costa Concordia'' struck a rock]] in the [[Tyrrhenian Sea]] just off the eastern shore of [[Isola del Giglio]]. This tore open a {{convert|50|m|abbr=on}} gash on the [[Port and starboard|port]] side of her hull, which soon flooded parts of the engine room, cutting power from the engines and ship services. With water flooding in and the ship [[List (watercraft)|listing]], she drifted back towards the island and grounded near shore, then rolled onto her starboard side, lying in an unsteady position on a rocky underwater ledge.\n\nThe evacuation of ''Costa Concordia'' took over six hours, and of the 3,229 passengers and 1,023 crew known to have been aboard, 32 died. [[Francesco Schettino]], the ship's captain at that time, was subsequently found guilty of manslaughter, causing a maritime accident, and [[The captain goes down with the ship|abandoning his ship]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36421474|title=Concordia skipper's sentence upheld|date=2016-05-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> The wreck was salvaged three years after the incident and then towed to the port of Genoa, where scrapping operations began.<ref name=\"Arrival in Genoa\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28508387|title=Costa Concordia wreck enters Genoa port for scrapping|date=27 July 2014|work=BBC news europe|accessdate=27 July 2014|publisher=BBC|agency=BBC}}</ref>\n\n== Concept and construction ==\n[[File:Costa Concordia in Piraeus.jpg|thumb|left|''Costa Concordia'' in [[Piraeus]], [[Greece]] on 30 November 2006]]\n''Costa Concordia'' was ordered in 2004 by [[Carnival Corporation]] from [[Fincantieri]] and built in the [[Sestri Ponente]] yard in [[Genoa]],<ref name=\"Fincantieri\">{{cite press release| title= Costa Crociere Orders A New Ship From Fincantieri With An Investment Of Around 450 Million Euros| url=http://www.fincantieri.it/cms/data/browse/news/000161.aspx| publisher=Fincantieri| date=19 January 2004| accessdate = 2 September 2011}}</ref> as yard number 6122.<ref name=Fakta /> At the vessel's [[ship naming and launching|launch]] at Sestri Ponente on 2&nbsp;September 2005,<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite press release| title=''Costa Concordia'', The Largest Italian Cruise Ship, is Launched in Genoa| url=http://www.fincantieri.it/cms/data/browse/news/000193.aspx| publisher=Fincantieri| date=2 September 2005| accessdate = 2 September 2011}}</ref> the champagne bottle, released by model [[Eva Herzigov\u00e1]], failed to break when swung against the hull the first time, an inauspicious omen in [[Sailors%27_superstitions|maritime superstition]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Levy |first=Megan |title=Cursed Concordia 'born bad, ended up worse' |url=http://www.smh.com.au/travel/travel-incidents/cursed-concordia-born-bad-ended-up-worse-20120116-1q1w2.html |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref> The ship was delivered to Costa on 30&nbsp;June 2006.<ref name=\"Fincantieri3\">{{cite press release| title=Costa Crociere Takes Delivery From Fincantieri Of The New Flagship ''Costa Concordia'' |url =http://www.fincantieri.it/cms/data/browse/news/000065.aspx |publisher  = [[Fincantieri]]| date=30 June 2006 |accessdate = 2 September 2011}}</ref> It cost [[Euro|\u20ac]]450 million (\u00a3372 million, {{US$|570 million}}) to build.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|title=Italy cruise ship ''Costa Concordia'' aground near Giglio|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16558910|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=14 January 2012|accessdate=14 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64gKkECCf?url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16558910 \n|archivedate=14 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy}}</ref>\nThe name ''[[wikt:concordia|Concordia]]'' was intended to express the wish for \"continuing harmony, unity, and peace between [[Europe]]an nations.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Malta on new liner's itinerary \n |url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20050919/local/malta-on-new-liners-itinerary.77802 \n |date=19 September 2005 \n |publisher=[[The Times (Malta)|The Times of Malta]] \n |accessdate=15 January 2012 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64hh6bzyK?url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20050919/local/malta-on-new-liners-itinerary.77802 \n |archivedate=15 January 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n''Costa Concordia'' was {{convert|290.20|m|ftin|0}} long, had a beam of {{convert|35.50|m|abbr=on}} and drew {{convert|8.20|m|abbr=on}} of water. She had a Diesel-electric power plant consisting of six [[V12 engine|12-cylinder]] [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V46C four-stroke medium-speed [[Diesel engine|Diesel generating sets]] with a combined output of {{convert|102780|hp|MW|1|order=flip|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"tradewinds\">{{Citation\n | title    = Costa Concordia 3,780 Berths, Cruise Vessel, Built 2006\n | url     = http://www.tradewindsnews.com/vessel?id=82C54167A64F8DE7\n | work    = [[TradeWinds (newspaper)|TradeWinds]]<br />Ship data from: Clarkson Research Services Limited\n | access-date = 28 January 2012\n}}</ref> These main generators provided power for all shipboard consumers from propulsion motors to hotel functions like lighting and air conditioning. The ship was propelled by two 21-megawatt electric motors coupled to fixed-pitch propellers.<ref>{{cite book\n | title    = Generazione di Energia A Bordo di Navi da Crociera\n | publisher  = Cetena\n | page    = 7\n | url     = http://diem.uniud.it/Conf_energia_navi_19-05-09.pdf\n | access-date = \n}}{{dead link|date=December 2012}}</ref> Her design service speed was {{convert|19.6|kn|0}},<ref name=Fakta>{{cite web\n | title    = M/S Costa Concordia\n | url     = http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/costa_concordia_2006.htm\n | work    = Fakta om Fartyg\n | language  = Swedish\n | access-date = 14 January 2012\n}}</ref> but during sea trials, she achieved a speed of {{convert|23|kn|lk=on|0}}.\n\n== Layout ==\n''Costa Concordia'' had 13 public decks, each named after a European state. Deck 1 was the lowest:<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Costa Concordia deck plans \n |url=http://www.atc.fi/old/decks/Costa_Concordia_deck_plans.pdf \n |publisher=ATC Cruises Ltd. \n |accessdate=30 December 2012\n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030040433/http://www.atc.fi/old/decks/Costa_Concordia_deck_plans.pdf \n |archivedate=30 October 2012 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n{|\n| valign=top |\n* Deck 1 Olanda (''Holland'')\n* Deck 2 Svezia (''Sweden'')\n* Deck 3 Belgio (''Belgium'')\n* Deck 4 Grecia (''Greece'')\n* Deck 5 Italia (''Italy'')\n* Deck 6 Gran Bretagna (''Great Britain''){{nb5}} {{nb5}}\n* Deck 7 Irlanda (''Ireland'')\n| valign=top |\n* Deck 8 Portogallo (''Portugal'')\n* Deck 9 Francia (''France'')\n* Deck 10 Germania (''Germany'')\n* Deck 11 Spagna (''Spain'')\n* Deck 12 Austria (''Austria'')\n* Deck 13 Polonia (''Poland'')\n|}\n\n== Amenities ==\n''Costa Concordia'' was outfitted with approximately 1,500 cabins; 505 with private balconies, and 55 with direct access to the Samsara Spa, which were considered Spa staterooms; 58&nbsp;suites had private balconies and 12 had direct access to the spa.{{clarify|date=January 2016}} ''Costa Concordia'' had one of the world's largest exercise facility areas at sea, the Samsara Spa, a two-level, {{convert|6000|m2|-2|abbr=on}} fitness center, with gym, a [[thalassotherapy]] pool, [[sauna]], [[Turkish bath]] and a solarium. The ship had four swimming pools, two with retractable roofs, five jacuzzis, five spas, and a poolside movie theatre on the main pool deck.<ref name=\"Costa\">{{cite web| title= Company Profile| url= http://www.costacruisesasia.com/B2C/PAO/Corporate/The+company/aboutourselves/aboutourselves.htm |publisher= [[Costa Crociere|Costa Crociere dba Costa Cruises]] |year= 2011 |accessdate= 2 September 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110708194121/http://www.costacruisesasia.com/B2C/PAO/Corporate/The+company/aboutourselves/aboutourselves.htm |archivedate= 8 July 2011 |df= dmy-all}}</ref> There were also five on-board restaurants, with Club Concordia and Samsara taking reservations-only dining. There were thirteen bars, including a cigar and [[Cognac (brandy)|cognac]] bar and a coffee and chocolate bar. Entertainment options included a three-level theatre, [[casino]], a futuristic disco, a children's area equipped with [[video game]]s and a basketball court. She also had aboard a [[Grand Prix motor racing]] simulator and an [[internet caf\u00e9]].<ref name=\"nypost\">{{cite news\n |agency=The Associated Press \n |title=At least 3 dead as cruise ship runs aground; captain arrested \n |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/international/three_coast_several_missing_after_Ztwzh4pOyI28VzooFByOnM/2 \n |newspaper=The New York Post \n |date=14 January 2012 \n |accessdate=30 December 2012\n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418212843/http://www.nypost.com/p/news/international/three_coast_several_missing_after_Ztwzh4pOyI28VzooFByOnM/2 \n |archivedate=18 April 2012 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n\n=== 2008 bow damage ===\nOn 22 November 2008, ''Costa Concordia'' suffered damage to her bow when high winds over the [[Sicily|Sicilian]] city of [[Palermo]] pushed the ship against its dock. There were no injuries and repairs started soon after.<ref name=\"nypost\" /><ref name=ToM>{{cite news\n | title    = Cruise liner damaged after leaving Malta\n | url     = http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20081123/local/cruise-liner-damaged-after-leaving-malta.234247\n | publisher  = [[The Times (Malta)|The Times of Malta]]\n | date    = 23 November 2008\n | accessdate = 12 January 2012\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | title    = Costa Concordia search operation resumes (underwater video)\n | url     = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16660403\n | work  = [[BBC News Online]]\n | date    = 12 January 2012\n | accessdate = 21 January 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Costa Concordia in 2009.jpg|thumb|''Costa Concordia'' after repairs on 31 July 2009]]\n\n===2012 grounding and partial sinking===\n{{Main|Costa Concordia disaster|l1=Costa Concordia disaster}}\n[[File:Cruise Ship Costa Concordia in Genoa Harbour - November 2010.jpg|thumb|''Costa Concordia'' in [[Genoa]], Italy on 24 November 2010]]\nOn 13 January 2012, under the command of Captain [[Francesco Schettino]], in calm seas and overcast weather, after departing [[Civitavecchia]], the port for Rome, Italy, on a 7-night cruise, at 21:45 local time (UTC+1), ''Costa Concordia'' hit a rock off [[Isola del Giglio]] ({{coord|42|21|55|N|10|55|17|E |name= Costa Concordia 2012 grounding |display=inline}}), on the western coast of Italy about {{convert|100|km|abbr=on}} northwest of [[Rome]].<ref name=\"rock1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/23/world/europe/costa-concordia-may-have-had-unregistered-passengers.html|title=Costa Concordia May Have Had Unregistered Passengers|author=Gaia Pianigiani|date=22 January 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"rock2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/24/costa-concordia-captain-blame-prosecutor|title=Costa Concordia captain not solely to blame, says prosecutor|author=John Hooper|date=24 January 2012|work=The Guardian |accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> A {{convert|53|m|ft|0|adj=on}} long gash was made in the port-side hull, along 3 compartments of the engine room (deck 0); resulting in power losses, leading to a loss of propulsion and loss of electrical systems, which crippled the ship. Taking on water, the vessel [[List (watercraft)|listed]] to the port side. Twenty-four minutes later, strong winds pushed the vessel back to Giglio Island, where she [[Ship grounding|grounded]] {{convert|500|m|yd|abbr=on}} north of the village of [[Giglio Porto]], resting on her [[Port and starboard|starboard]] side in shallow waters, with most of her starboard side underwater.<ref name=\"hole1\">{{Citation|title=Naufragio al Giglio, tre morti annegati Fermati comandante e primo ufficiale, Corriere de la Sera|date=14 January 2012|url=http://www.corriere.it/cronache/12_gennaio_14/nave-crociera-incagliata-morti_da423a42-3e72-11e1-8b52-5f77182bc574.shtml|newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]]|language=Italian |accessdate=30 December 2012}} Confirms that vessel was holed.</ref><ref name=\"hole2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/christopherbooker/9030330/The-EU-ignored-years-of-expert-warnings-on-cruise-ship-safety.html|title=The EU ignored years of expert warnings on cruise ship safety|author=Christopher Book|date=21 January 2012 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=30 December 2012}} Discusses stability issue when large modern ships are holed. Explains heeling first in direction of hole, then in opposite direction.</ref><ref name=\"BBC16561382\">{{cite news\n | first    = Alexis\n | last    = Akwagyiram\n | title    = Italy cruise ship Costa Concordia: Search for missing\n | url     = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16561382\n | work    = [[BBC News Online]]\n | date    = 14 January 2012\n | accessdate = 14 January 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Collision of Costa Concordia 24.jpg|thumb|right|''Costa Concordia'' after dawn with lifeboats at shore]]\nAlmost half of the ship remained above water, but it was in danger of sinking completely into a trough {{convert|70|m|ft|0}} deep.<ref>{{cite magazine\n |author=Marco Breath \n |title=Concordia at \u2018High Risk\u2019 of Sinking, Italian Minister Says \n |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-01-19/concordia-at-high-risk-of-sinking-italian-minister-says.html\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120722185616/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-01-19/concordia-at-high-risk-of-sinking-italian-minister-says.html\n |url-status=dead\n |archivedate=22 July 2012\n |magazine=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] \n |date=23 January 2012 \n |accessdate=31 December 2012\n}}</ref> Despite the gradual sinking of the ship, its complete loss of power, and its proximity to shore in calm seas, an order to abandon ship was not issued until over an hour after the initial impact. Although international maritime law requires all passengers to be evacuated within 30 minutes of an order to abandon ship, the evacuation of ''Costa Concordia'' took over six hours. At the time, she was carrying 3,206 passengers and 1,023 crew members.<ref name=\"CarnivalCorporation\">{{cite web\n | title    = Carnival Corporation & plc Statement Regarding Costa Concordia\n | url     = http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=200767&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1648204\n | publisher  = [[Carnival Corporation & plc]]\n | date    = 14 January 2012\n | accessdate = 24 January 2012\n}}</ref><ref name=\"AP140112\">{{cite news\n |last=Winfield \n |first=Nicole \n |author2=Frances D'Emilio \n |title=Coast guard: cruise ship runs aground off Italy, 3 bodies found; helicopters rescue others \n |url=http://www.wxyz.com/dpp/homepage_showcase/coast-guard-cruise-ship-runs-aground-off-italy-3-bodies-found-helicopters-rescue-others \n |publisher=[[WXYZ-TV]] \n |agency=The Associated Press \n |date=14 January 2012 \n |accessdate=24 January 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116220935/http://www.wxyz.com/dpp/homepage_showcase/coast-guard-cruise-ship-runs-aground-off-italy-3-bodies-found-helicopters-rescue-others \n |archivedate=16 January 2012 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> The accident resulted in 32 fatalities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/glogin?URI=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2014%2F05%2F14%2Fworld%2Feurope%2Fport-vies-to-dismantle-italian-cruise-ship.html%3F_r%3D0|title=Aging Tuscan Port Vies to Dismantle Costa Concordia|last=PIANIGIANI|first=GAIA|date=13 May 2014 |newspaper=NYTimes|accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-17472345 |title=Costa Concordia: Five more bodies found|date=22 March 2012 |work=BBC News |accessdate=23 March 2012}}</ref> The body of the last missing person, Indian crew member Russel Rebello, was recovered on 3 November 2014.<ref name=\"NBC3Nov\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/italy-corpse-found-costa-concordia-wreck-assumed-be-russel-rebello-n239981|title=Italy: Corpse Found in Costa Concordia Wreck 'Assumed' to Be Russel Rebello|date=3 November 2014|work=NBC News|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Salvage====\n{{Main|Costa Concordia disaster#Salvage|l1=''Costa Concordia'' salvage}}\n[[File:Costa Concordia salvage July crop.jpg|thumb|right|''Costa Concordia'' salvage operation in progress]]\n\nAn initial assessment by salvage expert company [[Smit International]] estimated that the removal of ''Costa Concordia'' and her 2,380 tonnes of fuel<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/15/us-italy-ship-idUSTRE80D08220120115|title=Two more bodies found on ship, three people rescued|date=15 January 2012|work=[[Reuters]] |last2=Denti |first2=Antonio |first1=Gavin|last1=Jones |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | title    = Two more bodies found in Costa Concordia shipwreck\n | url     = https://calgaryherald.com/news/more+bodies+found+Costa+Concordia+shipwreck/6037951/story.html\n | work    = The Calgary Herald\n | date    = 23 January 2012\n | accessdate = 23 January 2012\n | archiveurl = http://www.recentnews.ca/two-more-bodies-found-in-costa-concordia-shipwreck/ <!-- vandalism ? http://scs.mathletics.com/SignInIFrame.asp?ccode=CAN&host=www.mathletics.ca --> \n | archivedate = 31 December 2012\n}}</ref> could take up to 10 months.<ref name=BBC16782481>{{cite news\n | title    = Costa Concordia recovery 'will take up to 10 months'\n | url     = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16782481\n | work    = BBC News\n | date    = 29 January 2012\n | accessdate = 30 January 2012\n}}</ref> Smit advised that the ship had been damaged beyond the hope of economical repair and recommended it be written off as a [[constructive total loss]]. Smit was soon contracted to initially remove only Concordia's fuel.\n\nDuring the fuel removal operation, Smit reported that the ship had shifted {{convert|24|in|cm|-1|order=flip|abbr=on}} in the three weeks since her grounding, but that there was no immediate prospect of her breaking up or sinking deeper.<ref>{{cite news|title= Costa Concordia: stricken cruise ship has shifted 24 inches|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/9069093/Costa-Concordia-stricken-cruise-ship-has-shifted-24-inches.html| work= The Daily Telegraph|date = 8 February 2012| accessdate = 2 May 2012}}</ref> Removal of the fuel from the various fuel tanks distributed throughout the ship was completed in March 2012, later than Smit's initial estimates. This cleared the way to arrange for the ultimate salvaging and scrapping of the ship.\n\nOn 17 September 2013, ''Costa Concordia'' was brought to a vertical position through a [[Parbuckle_salvage|parbuckling]] procedure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2013/sep/16/concordia-salvage-operation-giglio-parbuckling-live-updates|title=Costa Concordia: salvage teams begin to right cruise ship \u2013 live updates|date=16 September 2013|author=Walker, Peter |accessdate=17 September 2013 |work=The Guardian |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fglobal%2F2013%2Fsep%2F16%2Fconcordia-salvage-operation-giglio-parbuckling-live-updates&date=2013-09-18|archivedate=18 September 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Parbuckling Project: Concordia wreck removal project informative website|url=http://www.theparbucklingproject.com/page.php?page=progetto|accessdate=13 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917133020/http://www.theparbucklingproject.com/page.php?page=progetto|archivedate=17 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The cost for salvaging the ship increased to $799 million.<ref>{{cite news |author=Gaia Pianigiani and Alan Cowell |title=Crews Right Cruise Ship in Waters Off Italy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/17/world/europe/operation-to-raise-costa-concordia-cruise-liner-in-italy.html |work=The New York Times |date=16 September 2013 |accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref> In addition, the ship had suffered severe hull deformations in two places. Titan Salvage, the company directing the salvage operations, estimated that the next phase of the salvage operation would be completed by early-to-mid-2014. After this \"floating\" operation, the ship would be towed to a salvage yard on the Italian mainland for scrapping or \"breaking\".<ref>{{cite news| author=Barbie Latza Nadeau| title=Costa Concordia salvage: Island celebrations and relief |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/17/world/europe/costa-concordia/?hpt=tr_c2 |work=CNN |date=17 September 2013 |accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 July 2014, work commenced to refloat ''Costa Concordia'' in preparation for towing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/14/costa-concordia-salvage-operation-refloat-liner|title=Costa Concordia: salvage team begins operation to refloat doomed liner |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=14 July 2014 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> At this point, the costs had risen to \u20ac1 billion. Including tow cost, \u20ac100 million for the ship to be broken up for scrap and the cost of repairing damage to Giglio island, the estimated final cost was expected to be \u20ac1.5 billion ($2 billion).<ref name=\"Reuters20140706\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/06/italy-concordia-costs-idUSL6N0PH0EO20140706 ''Costa Concordia capsizing costs over $2 billion for owners''] Maria Sheahan, Reuters.com, 6 July 2014.</ref><ref name=\"GeargeHatcher20140709\">[http://disasteratsea.com/index.php/costa-concordia-owner-faces-2-billion-in-costs/ ''Costa Concordia owner faces $2 billion in costs''] George Hatcher, ''Disaster at Sea'' blog, 9 July 2014.</ref> On 23 July, having been refloated, the ship commenced its final journey under tow at a speed of {{convert|2|kn|0}}, with a 14-ship escort, to be scrapped in Genoa.<ref name=\"FinalVoyage\">{{cite news|title=Rusting luxury liner Costa begins final voyage|url=http://www.europenews.net/index.php/sid/224057463/scat/88176adfdf246af5/ht/Rusting-luxury-liner-Costa-begins-final-voyage|accessdate=23 July 2014|publisher=Europe News.Net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729235427/http://www.europenews.net/index.php/sid/224057463/scat/88176adfdf246af5/ht/Rusting-luxury-liner-Costa-begins-final-voyage|archive-date=29 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/costa-concordia-makes-final-voyage-to-its-scrapyard-grave/story-fnizu68q-1226999771994|title=The Concordia makes its final voyage|work=NewsComAu |accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref> It arrived at port on 27 July, after a four-day journey. It was moored to a seawall at the port, awaiting dismantling processes.<ref name=\"CostaArrival\">{{cite news|title=Costa Concordia wreck completes final journey|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/10994004/Costa-Concordia-comes-home-to-die.html|accessdate=28 July 2014|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=\"CostaInterior\">{{cite news|title=Costa Concordia in pictures: Inside the cruise liner after two years underwater|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/worldnews/10985345/Costa-Concordia-in-pictures-Inside-the-cruise-liner-after-two-years-underwater.html|accessdate=5 January 2015|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Costa Concordia Abwracken.jpg|thumb|left|''Costa Concordia'' on 12 September 2015, being scrapped in the Superbacino dock in Genoa, Italy]]\n\nOn 11 May 2015, following initial dismantling, but still kept afloat by the salvage sponsons, the hull was towed {{convert|10|mi|km}} to the Superbacino dock in Genoa for removal of the upper decks.<ref>{{cite news |\nurl=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/160283/costa-concordia-to-embark-on-its-final-journey/ |date=7 May 2015 |title=Costa Concordia to embark on its final journey |publisher= World Maritime News}}</ref> The last of the sponsons were removed in August 2016 and the hull was taken in to a drydock on 1 September for final dismantling.<ref name=WMN201091>{{cite web |url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/201091/costa-concordia-sets-off-on-final-voyage-to-scrapyard/ |title=Costa Concordia Sets Off on Final Voyage to Scrapyard |publisher=World Maritime News |date=2 September 2016 |accessdate=4 September 2016}}</ref> Scrapping of the ship was completed on 7 July 2017.<ref name=WMN225190>{{cite web |url=http://worldmaritimenews.com/archives/225190/costa-concordia-saga-comes-to-an-end/ |title=Costa Concordia Saga Comes to an End |publisher=World Maritime News |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4119840/Ghost-ship-Wreck-tragic-Costa-Concordia-torn-apart-scrap-shipyard-five-years-cruise-liner-capsized-killing-32-people.html|title=Ghost ship: Wreck of tragic Costa Concordia is torn apart for scrap|author=|date=|website=dailymail.co.uk|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn 2010, ''Costa verde'' provided the setting for [[Jean-Luc Godard]]'s film ''[[Film Socialisme|Socialisme]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n | first    = Xan\n | last    = Brooks\n | title    = Costa Concordia provides setting for a 2010 Jean-Luc Godard film\n | url     = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jan/15/costa-concordia-jean-luc-godard\n | work    = The Guardian\n | date    = 15 January 2012\n | accessdate = 16 January 2012\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, U.S. poet and singer [[Patti Smith]] wrote and recorded parts of her album ''[[Banga (album)|Banga]]'' aboard the ship. The CD booklet includes photos taken of Smith and her band during their cruise.\n\nOn 11 April 2012, a documentary broadcast in the United Kingdom, titled ''Terror at Sea: The Sinking of the Costa Concordia'', and another first broadcast on Channel 4, titled ''The Sinking of the Concordia: Caught on Camera'', featured footage recorded by the passengers and crew.\n\nOn 14 July 2012, a documentary titled ''Cruise Ship Disaster: Inside the Concordia'', was first broadcast on the [[Discovery Channel]], ''CNN Presents: Cruise to Disaster'', first broadcast by [[CNN]]<ref>{{Citation| title= CNN Presents: Cruise to Disaster|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1207/14/cp.01.html| work=CNN| accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> and another, titled ''Inside Costa Concordia: Voices of Disaster'', was first broadcast by the [[National Geographic Channel]].<ref>{{Citation| title=Inside Costa Concordia: Voices of Disaster| url= http://natgeotv.com/asia/inside-costa-concordia-voices-of-disaster| publisher=National Geographic Channel| accessdate = 31 December 2012}}</ref> The season 39 ''[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]'' episode \"Why Ships Sink\" discusses the sinking of ''Costa Concordia''.<ref>{{Citation| author=Challis, J.| title=Nova: Why Ships Sink| url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/tech/why-ships-sink.html| publisher=[[PBS]], [[WGBH-TV|WGBH Educational Foundation]]| work=[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]| year=2012| accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> A later ''[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]'' season 42 episode \"Sunken Ship Rescue\" featured the salvage effort and race to refloat and remove the badly damaged Costa Concordia from the accident scene before the ship could break apart, risking an environmental catastrophe.<ref>{{Citation| author=WGBH Boston| title=Nova: Sunken Ship Rescue| url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/tech/sunken-ship-rescue.html| publisher=[[PBS]], [[WGBH-TV|WGBH Educational Foundation]]| work=[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]]| year=2015|accessdate =21 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February 2013, ABC's ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'' aired a special on the sinking and interviews with the survivors following the engine fire on {{ship||Carnival Triumph}}.<ref>{{cite news | author=Lateef Mungin and Steve Almasy | title=Crippled cruise ship returns; passengers happy to be back | url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/02/14/travel/cruise-ship-fire/index.html | work=CNN | date=15 February 2013 | accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn Paolo Sorrentino's 2013 film ''[[The Great Beauty]]'', the wreckage of ''Costa Concordia'' is featured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/09/movies/paolo-sorrentinos-great-beauty-explores-italys-decline.html|title=Paolo Sorrentino\u2019s \u2018Great Beauty\u2019 Explores Italy\u2019s Decline|last=Donadio|first=Rachel|date=8 September 2013 |work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 January 2018 |language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn the 2016 album ''Teens of Denial'', \"The Ballad of the Costa Concordia\", written by Will Toledo from indie rock band [[Car Seat Headrest]], uses the disaster as a metaphor for a personal breakdown.<ref>{{cite magazine |\nurl=http://www.bkmag.com/2016/06/21/20-best-songs-of-2016-so-far/?singlepage=1 | date=21 June 2012 |title=A Highly Subjective List of the 20 Best Songs of 2016 (So Far) |magazine=Brooklyn Magazine}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}